July 18, 2018

Ensemble Modeling

  • Build a prediction model
    • combine the strengths of basic simpler models together
    • Example:
      • bagging (8.7), random forest (chapter 15)
      • bayesian method for non-parametric regression
  • Method has two tasks
    • develop population of base model using training data
    • combine the models for composite prediction
  • Why ensemble modeling?
    • reduce prediction variability
    • example: decision trees have high variability
    • when data is large, this helps to fit model in convenient time

Bagging

  • Take \(B\) bootstrap samples from the training data set
  • Obtain prediction \(\hat f^b(x)\) from \(b\)th bootstrap sample
  • Finally obtain prediction
    • for regression: \[\hat f_{bag}(x) = \frac 1 B \sum_{b=1}^B \hat f^b(x)\]
    • for classification: use majority vote for a class
  • OOB error is computed using Out Of Bag data (validation set)
    • training is usually terminated once OOB error stabilizes
  • Test error is computed using test data set
  • Bagging is very useful for trees. Since trees are less biased with high variability.

Random Forest

  • Similar to bagging
    • but for each tree a random set of \(m\) variables are considered
      • this creates uncorrelated trees for each bootstrap sample
    • in bagging, all the trees are correlated
      • this does not help reduce prediction error
  • Choice of \(m\) out of \(p\) explanatory variables
    • classification problem: default \(m = \lfloor \sqrt{p} \rfloor\)
    • regression problem: default \(m = \lfloor p/3 \rfloor\)
    • actual value of \(m\) can be obtained by tuning using validation data set

Fitting a Decision Tree

library(tree)
library(ISLR)
dat <- Carseats[,-1]
dat$High <- factor(ifelse(Carseats$Sales <= 8,"No","Yes"))
fit.tree <- tree(High ~ . , dat )
summary(fit.tree)
##

Fitting tree with training data

set.seed (2)
N <- nrow(dat)
train <- sample(1:N, 200)
dat.test <- dat[-train ,]
fit.tree1 <- tree(High ~. , dat, subset=train)
tree.pred <- predict(fit.tree1, dat.test, type="class")
(rs <- table(tree.pred ,dat.test$High))
##          
## tree.pred No Yes
##       No  86  27
##       Yes 30  57
(rs[1,1]+rs[2,2]) /sum(rs)
## [1] 0.715

Improving Tree fit by cross-validation

set.seed(3)
cv.dat <- cv.tree(fit.tree1, FUN = prune.misclass )
cv.dat

Showing cross-validation result

par(mfrow=c(1,2))
plot(cv.dat$size ,cv.dat$dev ,type="b")
plot(cv.dat$k ,cv.dat$dev ,type="b")

Pruning the tree

prune.tree <- prune.misclass(fit.tree1, best = 9)
plot(prune.tree)
text(prune.tree,pretty=0)

Results after pruning

tree.pred <- predict(prune.tree, dat.test, type="class")
(rs <- table(tree.pred ,dat.test$High))
##          
## tree.pred No Yes
##       No  94  24
##       Yes 22  60
(rs[1,1]+rs[2,2]) /sum(rs)
## [1] 0.77

Homework Problem

In this lecture, a classification tree was applied to the Carseats data set after converting Sales into a qualitative response (factor) variable. Now we will seek to predict Sales using regression trees and related approaches, treating the response as a quantitative variable.

  1. Split the data set into a training set and a test set.
  2. Fit a regression tree to the training set. Plot the tree, and interpret the results. What test MSE do you obtain?
  3. Use cross-validation in order to determine the optimal level of tree complexity. Does pruning the tree improve the test MSE?
  4. Use the bagging approach in order to analyze this data. What test MSE do you obtain? Use the importance() function to determine which variables are most important.
  5. Use random forests to analyze this data as well
